# UI Runtime Performance Guardrails

- Do not run repeated `Find*`, `GetComponent*`, `Q`, `Query`, `new List`, string concatenation, or expensive layout calculations inside `Update`/`LateUpdate`; cache references and computed results.
- Refresh UI on state changes, dirty flags, or events, not every frame; reject the assumption that redraw must be continuous.
- Do not rebuild UI Toolkit visual trees every frame, repeatedly create/delete children, or continuously write inline `style` values; use UXML structure, cached elements, and class toggles.
- Prefer `AddToClassList`, `RemoveFromClassList`, and `EnableInClassList` for visual state; avoid style churn when a USS class can express the state.
- Legacy uGUI exceptions must be explicit; do not chain expensive flows such as `Canvas.ForceUpdateCanvases`, `LayoutRebuilder`, `ContentSizeFitter`, or repeated `SetActive` without a clear reason.
- For frequently updated text/icon fields, keep the previous value and write to UI only when the value changes to reduce allocations and rebuilds.
- Do not duplicate hidden state for performance; optimization must not break the owning `GameState` or presenter contract.

## Example

```csharp
// BAD: Visual tree query, new string, and refresh every frame.
private void Update()
{
    root.Q<Label>("money-label").text = $"Coins: {_gameState.Money:F0}";
    root.Q("inventory-panel").EnableInClassList("is-open", _state.IsInventoryOpen);
}

// GOOD: Cache elements and write only when values change.
if (_lastMoney != _gameState.Money)
{
    _lastMoney = _gameState.Money;
    _moneyText.text = _lastMoney.ToString("F0");
}

_inventoryPanel.EnableInClassList("is-open", _state.IsInventoryOpen);
```
